steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"857eh","text":"Place the battery into a container that is sealable with a vented lid, such as a five gallon bucket. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cjjgv","text":"Carefully pour the salt/water solution into the container holding the battery so that it is completely submerged and covered in several inches of water. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8hafc","text":"Check for activity from the battery and cover the bucket with the vented lid. Bubbles should emerge from the battery's terminal port as electrolysis begins. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"391rv","text":"Monitor the battery and the lid regularly. It is possible that residue may develop along the surface of the salt/water solution, and it may take several changes of the water for the battery to completely discharge. Complete discharge of the battery could take many days, depending on the size and build of the battery. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"17h1i","text":"Battery is safe to be recycled or disposed of when electrolysis is complete and voltage is at a low level. Store the battery in a sealable plastic bag until it is ready to be disposed of. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6ge17","text":"Dissolve Non-Iodized Salt into Water in an appropriate container following the measurements outlined in the chart below.
